{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c1fcabea-2ed6-4753-8710-e150679636dd","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application` overrides no longer exist. Instead, use the **lifecycle events API** on the `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n    window.Stopped += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n    window.Resumed += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\nPlace this override in your `App` class (which still inherits from `Application`).\n\n**Key mappings:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI Window Event |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Window.Created` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Window.Stopped` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Window.Resumed` |\n\nAdditional events like `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Backgrounding`, and `Destroying` are also available for finer-grained control. You can also hook platform-specific lifecycle events via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents()` in `MauiProgram.cs` if needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3bca928c-66a9-4db9-81ff-ca3c0eefb1ac","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI, specifically about the Application lifecycle methods (OnStart, OnSleep, OnResume). This is a knowledge question I can answer directly.","outputTokens":365,"requestId":"110F:3AF65D:C31524:E3D478:69FE8667"},"id":"79894f16-eac9-44a1-8f8a-b0a10fcfc2c8","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:57:18.773Z","parentId":"54377837-2fea-44e2-9c61-19d9869ccfb3"}
